  "text": "Ebbinghaus ' (1885/1913) concept of the learning curve has framed a substantial body of work on simulation. Traces of this idea are evident in contemporary simulation education literature [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Cook et al. , 2013 . The learning curve describes how fast individuals learn information, and is seen as one way of deciding the difficulty of a given task. After the first repetition, the sharpest increase of the curve occurs but then gradually evens out as less and less new information is retained after each repetition. As a framework for conceiving and designing-in difficulty, it remains common where the focus is on learning particular psychomotor skills (e.g. endoscopy, bronchoscopy, laparoscopy).",
